any H. officinalis variety. Plant only during dry season (December-March). Requires raised beds 30cm high with 60% sand/gravel mix. Provide rain protection during monsoon. Expect to replace annually. Harvest before monsoon arrival.", "availability": "Indian Ayurvedic nurseries, Spices Board sources, Kashmir seed suppliers", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "H. officinalis f. albus (White)", "slug": "h-officinalis-f-albus-white", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Slightly more adaptable than blue. Same requirements as standard variety. White flowers may perform better in high elevation monsoon-edge conditions. Experimental only.", "availability": "Import from international suppliers, limited Indian availability", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "H. officinalis subsp. aristatus (Dwarf)", "slug": "h-officinalis-subsp-aristatus-dwarf", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Mountain subspecies may tolerate high-elevation Kerala conditions better. Compact size allows for easier rain protection. Still requires dry season planting and excellent drainage. Experimental.", "availability": "Import from European suppliers", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "Agastache foeniculum (Anise Hyssop)", "slug": "agastache-foeniculum-anise-hyssop", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Modern cultivar", "traits": "90cm tall, lighter green foliage, less bushy than species", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High, productive plant for both leaves and flowers", "growing_notes": "Performs moderately well in Brisbane with good drainage. More humidity-tolerant than Hyssopus but can get powdery mildew in wet periods. Ensure good air circulation. Self-seeds readily. Good for tea and culinary use. Zones 3-8, may struggle in hottest Brisbane summers. Plant in location with afternoon shade. Ornamental selection for Brisbane gardens. Golden foliage needs part shade to prevent burning. Same growing requirements as species. Unique color adds interest. White flowers more visible to pollinators. Good Brisbane performance with afternoon shade. Well-drained soil essential. Good for Brisbane with proper care. Lighter foliage may be more heat-sensitive - provide shade.", "availability": "Wisconsin Horticulture suppliers, specialty nurseries", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "Agastache rugosa (Korean Mint)", "slug": "agastache-rugosa-korean-mint", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to East Asia (Korea, China, Japan, Vietnam, Laos)", "traits": "60cm tall, glossy green leaves with purple undersides, triangular shaped", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High, vigorous grower", "growing_notes": "EXCELLENT FOR BRISBANE - this is the best Agastache for humid subtropical climates! Native to moist grasslands and wet environments. Tolerates humidity and wet soils much better than other species. Strong mint fragrance. Used in Korean traditional medicine. Zones 5-9. Can handle Brisbane''s wet summers. Still needs good drainage but more forgiving.", "availability": "Asian seed suppliers, specialty herb nurseries", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "A. rugosa f. albiflora (White Korean Mint)", "slug": "a-rugosa-f-albiflora-white-korean-mint", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Dutch hybrid, Royal Horticultural Society Award of Garden Merit", "traits": "90cm tall, robust stems, sterile (doesn''t self-seed)", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Excellent, continuous blooming", "growing_notes": "Same excellent humidity tolerance as species. Good for Brisbane. Ornamental white form.", "availability": "Select Seeds, specialty Asian herb suppliers", "sort_order": 7}, {"name": "Kudos™ Series (A. rugosa hybrids)", "slug": "kudos-series-a-rugosa-hybrids", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Modern hybrid, patented variety", "traits": "Upright habit, blue-green foliage", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "HIGHLY RECOMMENDED FOR BRISBANE! Purpose-bred for humid, wet conditions that Brisbane experiences. Most adaptable Agastache series for subtropical climates. Compact size good for containers and small gardens. Dense calyxes hold color even after flowers fade. Excellent vigor and weather tolerance. EXCELLENT FOR BRISBANE - specifically bred as ''very good performer in heat and humidity''. One of the best choices for subtropical conditions. Tolerates both heat and moisture. Well-drained soil still important.", "availability": "Sandy''s Plants, specialty nurseries", "sort_order": 8}, {"name": "Agastache mexicana (Mexican Giant Hyssop)", "slug": "agastache-mexicana-mexican-giant-hyssop", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to Mexico", "traits": "Large pink flower spikes, gray-green foliage", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Moderate Brisbane suitability - native to dry areas but can adapt. Needs excellent drainage. Best in drier months. Good hummingbird attractor (substitute: rainbow lorikeets in Brisbane). Zones 5. Drought tolerant but grows well in regular garden conditions. Good Brisbane adaptability. Good moisture tolerance. Suitable for Brisbane with good drainage.", "availability": "Garden Design specialists", "sort_order": 9}, {"name": "Poquito™ Series (compact hybrids)", "slug": "poquito-series-compact-hybrids", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "", "traits": "Very compact 30-40cm, perfect for containers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Small size makes them more manageable in Brisbane heat. Good for container growing on patios with good air flow.", "availability": "High Country Gardens", "sort_order": 10}, {"name": "MEANT TO BEE® Series", "slug": "meant-to-bee-series", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "", "traits": "30cm compact, pink and orange flowers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Good for Brisbane containers. Zones 7-10 - well-suited to subtropical climate. Very compact, excellent for Brisbane containers and small spaces.", "availability": "Costa Farms", "sort_order": 11}, {"name": "Agastache rugosa (Korean Mint)", "slug": "agastache-rugosa-korean-mint", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "East Asia - moist grasslands, valleys, stream banks", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "BEST CHOICE for Kerala monsoon climate. Native to wet Asian environments similar to Kerala conditions. Tolerates high humidity and moisture better than any other Agastache. Plant in raised beds during dry season (December-March). May need protection from direct monsoon deluge but can handle ambient moisture. Use in herb gardens for traditional medicine (similar uses to brahmi). Harvest before peak monsoon. Second-best choice for Kerala. Inherits A. rugosa''s moisture tolerance. More ornamental than species. Requires raised beds, good drainage, but handles humidity. Plant during dry season. May succeed where true hyssop fails.", "availability": "Import from international suppliers", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "Kudos™ Series", "slug": "kudos-series", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "Specifically bred for moisture tolerance. ''Kudos Ambrosia'' and ''Kudos Coral'' worth trying in Kerala high-elevation gardens. Compact size allows for easier management and rain protection. Experimental but promising. Bred for heat AND humidity tolerance. May adapt to Kerala conditions better than most. Still requires dry season planting and good drainage. Worth experimental trial.", "availability": "Import from international specialty suppliers", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "Bacopa monnieri (Standard)", "slug": "bacopa-monnieri-standard", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Native to wetlands of India, Southeast Asia, Australia, globally distributed", "traits": "Creeping herb <30cm tall, spreading 90cm, succulent oblong leaves 4-6mm thick", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "EXCELLENT FOR BRISBANE! Thrives in wetland areas, bog gardens, pond edges. Perfect for Brisbane''s wet conditions that challenge true hyssop. Grows in waterlogged soil or even submerged in shallow water. Can tolerate brackish conditions. Good ground cover for wet areas. Hardy Zones 8-11. Used in Ayurvedic medicine for cognitive enhancement.", "availability": "Native to Australia - available at aquatic plant nurseries, bog garden specialists", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "Bacopa monnieri (Kerala Native Brahmi)", "slug": "bacopa-monnieri-kerala-native-brahmi", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Indigenous to India, including Kerala - grows naturally in marshy areas throughout the region", "traits": "Creeping perennial herb, 15cm tall, succulent oblong leaves arranged oppositely, forms dense mat", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High - fast-growing, can be harvested continuously. Leaves are the medicinal part.", "growing_notes": "IDEAL FOR KERALA! This is what should be grown instead of Hyssopus officinalis in Kerala. Perfectly adapted to monsoon climate - actually requires constant moisture. Thrives in waterlogged soil. Can be grown in: (1) Bog gardens; (2) Pond edges; (3) Paddy field borders; (4) Water gardens; (5) Hydroponic systems; (6) Containers kept constantly wet. Traditional Ayurvedic herb for memory, cognitive function, anxiety relief. Extensively used in Kerala traditional medicine.", "availability": "Widely available throughout Kerala - local Ayurvedic plant nurseries, traditional medicine suppliers, agricultural centers, can be collected from wild populations (with permission)", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "Kerala Local Ecotypes", "slug": "kerala-local-ecotypes", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 7}], "variety_count": 20}'::jsonb,
  variety_count = 20, status = 'parsed'
WHERE source_path = 'brainstorm-inbox/import-payloads/hyssop.json';

UPDATE public.garden_import_queue SET payload = '{"species": "Ice Cream Bean", "species_slug": "ice-cream-bean", "varieties": [{"name": "1. Inga edulis ‘Standard Commercial’", "slug": "1-inga-edulis-standard-commercial", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Central/South America, widely distributed, commercially available in Australia since 1990s", "traits": "Fast-growing evergreen tree to 15-30m height, broad spreading canopy, dark green pinnate leaves, white-yellow pompom flowers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Fruits 2-3 times yearly. Mature trees produce 100-300+ pods annually under optimal conditions", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Daleys Fruit Trees, Fruitopia Nursery (Brisbane), Heaven on Earth Fruit Trees (FNQ), Greenpatch Organic Seeds, The Australian Plant Shop", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "2. Inga edulis ‘Long Pod Selection’", "slug": "2-inga-edulis-long-pod-selection", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Amazonian Peru selection, documented 2m+ pods, cultivated 100+ years", "traits": "Large spreading tree 20-30m. Produces extraordinarily long pods, often spirally twisted. Bronze-green foliage", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High productivity, 200-400 pods per mature tree. Extended harvest season", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Specialty subtropical fruit nurseries, occasionally at Daleys as ‘Giant Ice Cream Bean’", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "3. Inga edulis ‘Female Type’ (Black Seed Selection)", "slug": "3-inga-edulis-female-type-black-seed-selection", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Traditional Amazonian farmer selection, cultivated for centuries. Distinguished by deep black ‘female’ seeds", "traits": "Vigorous tree 15-25m, broad canopy. Seeds are deep purplish-black (vs. lighter olive tones in ‘male’ types)", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Significantly higher productivity than ‘male’ types - Amazonian farmers preferentially propagate this form. 250-500 pods per tree", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Rare Fruit Club WA members, specialty imports. Request ‘female’ or ‘black seed’ type when ordering", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "4. Inga densiflora ‘Brisbane Short Pod’", "slug": "4-inga-densiflora-brisbane-short-pod", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Central America (Costa Rica, Venezuela), naturalized in Brisbane region 1980s-1990s", "traits": "Large attractive tree with spreading branches. Produces short hairy yellow-colored pods (distinctive from I. edulis)", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Very productive, fruits 2-3 times per year. Compact pods make harvesting easier", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Daleys Fruit Trees (often labeled as I. edulis), local Brisbane nurseries, propagates readily from seed", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "5. Inga feuillei ‘Pacay’", "slug": "5-inga-feuillei-pacay", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Peru (particularly Andean valleys), traditional cultivar, 500+ years cultivation history", "traits": "Rounded-depressed spreading tree 20-40’, more cold-hardy than I. edulis. Covered with white lenticels on young branches", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate to high productivity. Excellent fruit quality makes up for slightly smaller yields", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Specialty tropical fruit importers, occasionally available through Australian subtropical fruit networks", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "6. Inga spectabilis ‘Machete’ / ‘Guaba de Machete’", "slug": "6-inga-spectabilis-machete-guaba-de-machete", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Ecuador, Colombia. Named ‘machete’ for the wide, flat pod shape resembling a machete blade", "traits": "Fast-growing tree to 40’, distinctive wide leaves. Spectacular white brush-like flowers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate yields, exceptional quality. Pods are large and wide, providing substantial pulp per pod", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Rare, specialty importers only. AKME Gardens (USA) carries seedlings - international shipping may be possible", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "7. Inga vera (Syn. Inga edulis var. vera)", "slug": "7-inga-vera-syn-inga-edulis-var-vera", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Tropical America, closely related to I. edulis. Some taxonomists consider it synonymous", "traits": "Medium to large tree 30-60’, spreading canopy. Very similar growth habit to I. edulis", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good productivity, 2-3 fruiting periods annually", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Available through specialist seed suppliers, sometimes marketed interchangeably with I. edulis", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "8. Inga laurina ‘White Inga’ / ‘Ingá-mirim’", "slug": "8-inga-laurina-white-inga-ing-mirim", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Brazil (widespread throughout), Mexico to Argentina. Called ‘small ice-cream bean’ due to petite pods", "traits": "Smaller tree 15-20m, dense low rounded crown. Distinctive leaves set it apart from other Inga. Tolerates drier climates", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Numerous small pods compensate for size. Very productive given tree dimensions", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Specialty suppliers. Real Sweet Farms (USA) has seedlings - check Australian import options", "sort_order": 7}, {"name": "9. Inga cinnamomea ‘Guaçú’ / ‘Inga-açu’", "slug": "9-inga-cinnamomea-gua-inga-a-u", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Amazon region (Brazil, Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador), riverine floodplain specialist", "traits": "Large evergreen tree 10-25m, open crown. Thrives in wet conditions, waterlogging-tolerant", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High productivity in suitable conditions. Excellent sarcotesta (pulp) quantity", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Rare in Australia. AKME Gardens (USA) occasionally has stock. Consider seed imports from Brazilian suppliers", "sort_order": 8}, {"name": "10. Inga capitata", "slug": "10-inga-capitata", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Guianas, Eastern Amazonia", "traits": "Medium-sized tree, similar growth habit to other Inga species", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate productivity, valued locally but less commonly cultivated than I. edulis", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Very rare, specialist collectors only", "sort_order": 9}, {"name": "1. Inga edulis ‘Standard Tropical Form’", "slug": "1-inga-edulis-standard-tropical-form", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Central/South America, naturalized across tropics. Available in Kerala since early 2000s", "traits": "Evergreen tree 20-30m, dense spreading canopy provides excellent shade. Rapid growth - 3-5m annually under optimal conditions", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Outstanding in Kerala’s climate - fruits 2-3 times annually with 300-500 pods per mature tree", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Kerala Nursery (Ayush Kerala), Veliyath Gardens (Kerala), local agricultural nurseries in Thiruvalla region", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "2. Inga edulis ‘Amazonian Long Pod’", "slug": "2-inga-edulis-amazonian-long-pod", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Western Amazon (Peru, Ecuador, Brazil), traditional selection over 500+ years", "traits": "Large tree 25-30m, broad umbrella-shaped canopy. Spirally twisted pods characteristic", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Very high - mature trees produce 400-600 pods annually. Long harvest season", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Specialty seed suppliers, international tropical fruit networks. Seeds Del Mundo (Europe) ships to India", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "3. Inga edulis ‘Female Type’ (Deep Black Seed)", "slug": "3-inga-edulis-female-type-deep-black-seed", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Amazon basin, traditional indigenous selection. Seeds characterized by deep purplish-black color", "traits": "Vigorous tree 20-28m, dense foliage. Distinguished from ‘male’ types by darker seeds and superior fruiting", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Dramatically higher than ‘male’ seed types - 400-700 pods per tree in Kerala’s optimal conditions", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Source from reputable Kerala nurseries with specific request for ‘female’/‘black seed’ selections. Import seeds from Amazonian suppliers", "sort_order": 2}, {"name": "4. Inga feuillei ‘Pacay’", "slug": "4-inga-feuillei-pacay", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Peru (Andean and coastal valleys), centuries of cultivation, pre-Columbian heritage", "traits": "Rounded spreading tree 15-30m, more compact than I. edulis. Wide ecological range including drier areas", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good productivity, 200-400 pods per tree. Excellent fruit quality compensates for smaller size", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "International seed suppliers. Has been introduced to Polynesia, Italy, California - Kerala introduction feasible", "sort_order": 3}, {"name": "5. Inga spectabilis ‘Guaba de Machete’", "slug": "5-inga-spectabilis-guaba-de-machete", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Ecuador, Colombia, widespread in Andean foothills. Named for machete-blade shape", "traits": "Fast-growing to 30-40’, attractive broad leaves. Showy white brush flowers highly ornamental", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate to high productivity. Large wide pods provide substantial pulp volume", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Limited availability. Source through international tropical fruit networks or seed exchanges", "sort_order": 4}, {"name": "6. Inga vera", "slug": "6-inga-vera", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Throughout tropical America, sometimes considered synonym of I. edulis", "traits": "Large spreading tree 30-60’, very similar to I. edulis in appearance and growth", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good productivity, multiple fruiting periods annually", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Often marketed interchangeably with I. edulis. Available through seed suppliers", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "7. Inga cinnamomea ‘Inga-açu’ / ‘Guaçú’", "slug": "7-inga-cinnamomea-inga-a-u-gua", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Amazon basin (Brazil, Peru, Ecuador, Colombia), riverine floodplain specialist", "traits": "Large evergreen tree 15-25m, open crown structure. Thrives in waterlogged conditions", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High productivity in wetland/waterlogged sites. Superior pulp quality and quantity", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Rare. Source from Brazilian seed suppliers or botanical garden networks", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "8. Inga laurina ‘Ingá-mirim’ / White Inga", "slug": "8-inga-laurina-ing-mirim-white-inga", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Brazil (throughout), Mexico to Argentina. ‘Ingá-mirim’ = small ice cream bean in Portuguese", "traits": "Compact tree 15-20m with dense rounded crown. More drought-tolerant than most Inga species", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Prolific - numerous small pods. High productivity relative to tree size", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Brazilian nurseries, international seed exchanges. Veliyath Gardens may source on request", "sort_order": 7}, {"name": "9. Inga capitata", "slug": "9-inga-capitata", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Guianas and Eastern Amazonia", "traits": "Medium tree with typical Inga growth characteristics", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate productivity, less commonly cultivated", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Very rare, specialist botanical collections only", "sort_order": 8}, {"name": "10. Inga edulis var. parvifolia ‘Cipo Brazilian Minor’", "slug": "10-inga-edulis-var-parvifolia-cipo-brazilian-minor", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Brazil, regional selection with dwarfing characteristics", "traits": "Semi-dwarf variety with dwarfing behavior, smaller more manageable tree 8-15m. Maintains I. edulis fruit quality", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good productivity for smaller tree. Earlier fruiting than standard types", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Specialty suppliers. AKME Gardens (USA) carries this variety - explore Indian import options", "sort_order": 9}, {"name": "11. Inga edulis forma typica ‘Cipo Porto Yard Long’", "slug": "11-inga-edulis-forma-typica-cipo-porto-yard-long", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Brazil (Porto region), selection for extreme pod length", "traits": "Standard I. edulis growth habit, large spreading tree. Selected specifically for extraordinarily long pods", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High productivity, spectacular pod size increases pulp volume per pod", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "AKME Gardens carries this variety. Brazilian seed suppliers", "sort_order": 10}], "variety_count": 21}'::jsonb,
